> If ever there was a fusion food, tacos al pastor would be it. Although it looms
> large in the canon of Mexican tacos, the original recipe was inspired by
> Lebanese immigrants, who adapted it from shawarma. It typically features pork,
> but we're making it veggie-friendly by swapping in chorizo veggie crumbles.
> The wheat protein's mild heat works surprisingly well with cubes of sweet
> pineapple and slices of poblano.

Wash and dry all produce. Core and seed @Poblano Pepper{1}, then thinly slice
crosswise. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @White Onion{1}. Finely dice a few
slices until you have 3 TBSP diced onion and set aside for garnish. Drain
@Pineapple{4%oz}. Cut @Lime{1} into wedges. Pick @Cilantro{1/4%oz} leaves from
stems; discard stems.

Heat a drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat.
Add poblano and sliced onion. Cook, tossing, until lightly charred,
~{5-6%minutes}. Remove from pan and set aside.

Heat another drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add pineapple
to pan and cook, tossing, until lightly browned, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @Veggie Chorizo Crumbles{8%oz} to pan. Cook, tossing, until lightly browned,
~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tsp} (we sent more) and
@Chipotle Powder{1%tsp} (to taste—start with a pinch and go up from there).
Cook until fragrant, about ~{1%minute}.

Meanwhile, wrap @Flour Tortillas{6} in a damp #paper towel{} and microwave on
high until warm, about ~{30%seconds}.

> TIP: Alternatively, wrap tortillas in foil and warm in oven for 5 minutes at
> 400 degrees.

Spread a bit of @Sour Cream{4%tbsp} on each tortilla, then top with seitan
mixture, veggies, diced onion, and cilantro. Serve with lime wedges on the
side for squeezing over.

@Salt{} and @Pepper{} as needed for seasoning.